Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_648
Response Text: Help consolidate the opportunities! Too often there are events celebrating the same cultural groups on the same days, so these events end up competing with each other and creating a competitive atmosphere between these organizations, when these cultural organizations should be working together. These organizations often have the same goals, so it doesn't make sense for these organizations to be in competition for attendance and advertisement of their events-- the market gets saturated with the events and the attendees get lost on which one to go to. So ultimately, the attendee will choose the one closest to them/better parking or the one that has more activities (which are often for the orgs with more money). I especially think of COA ESB-MACC, where you see their events and compare it to Mexic-arte's La Fete Cinco de Mayo celebration (which by the way was a collab with a bunch of other orgs) and the Macc's La Mujer celebration, for example--- there's a huge difference because of funding! While I understand mexic-arte earns profits, it's disappointing that the city's own cultural events aren't the biggest and brightest! And let me tell you, this is not the fault of staff at the MACC, it's simply due to lack of funding for the macc. It's also interesting that the city choses to celebrate Cinco de Mayo when that is not a true mexican holiday and there are a ton of myths around it, but yet you have the City of Austin council members using that day as a way to celebrate Hispanic culture in Austin. Overall, I think ACME can support these organizations by starting internally with the City itself: AARC, Carver, and MACC. These sites should be more known by COA residents, and should be known more than a for profit or non-profit cultural organization in austin. It's hypocritical otherwise. So, im glad you all are doing the work of making this better.

